        <name>19.2.5.3 T Recognising an Exact Equation</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Solve the equation \({@f1@}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} + {@y*diff(f1,x)@} = {@gg@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\({@gg@} {@int(gg,x)@} {@diff(gg,x)@}\)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(y =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&amp;nbsp; \(+ \dfrac{C}{{@f1@}}\) [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Notice that in exact form  \[ f(x){\mathrm{d}y\over \mathrm{d}x}+y\ f'(x)=g(x)\] here \(f(x) = {@f1@}\) and \(g(x) = {@gg@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We may rewrite the equation then as \( \dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}({@ff@}) = {@gg@}\). Integrating both sides yields \({@ff@} = {@int(gg,x)@} + C\), where \(C\) is some constant.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We may then rearrange to find \(y\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[ y = {@ta1@}+ \frac{C}{{@f1@}}.\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
